I just created this prompt for a PWA smarthome/IoT dashboard. I want to use this with Opus. If there's anything I missed, please let mw know, @npub18ams6ewn5aj2n3wt2qawzglx9mr4nzksxhvrdc4gzrecw7n5tvjqctp424@momostr.pink
_____

Create a dashboard app for smarthome and IoT. It is very important that this is a PWA that can run offline. I want it to be able to connect to devices in a local network, but also online.

The dashboard should support HTTP requests (all methods), WebSocket and MQTT, including support for multiple MQTT brokers or WebSocket servers. Optionally, you can add support for the Constrained Application Protocol (CoAP).

The user should be able to create as many dashboards as he wants. The dashboards can use a JSON-based file format. Make sure the JSON is well formatted so that it can be read by humans using any text editor. Dashboards can be saved as a file and loaded from a file.

A dashboard can contain the following elements:
- text display that shows output
- text fields for data to send to a server or broker
- checkboxes with multiple choices
- radio buttons with one out of multiple choices
- buttons with one action
- switches with 2 actions
- non-binary switches with 3 or more actions
- image and video feed display for webcams
- variables and other things that enable elemwnts to take data from other elements

Server and broker URLs can be defined either per dashboard or per element. Maybe also a mix of both.

Optionally, you could implement some premade templates, including one for Tasmota devices. But please also let the user create a dashboard from scratch.

For future expansions, add Nostr login, just in case a custom or official NIP for smarthome or IoT should ever emerge.

映像品質を維持しながら、エンド・ツー・エンドの拡散生成を100～200倍高速化できる映像生成高速化フレームワーク、TurboDiffusionを紹介する。

TurboDiffusionは、主に次のようないくつかのコンポーネントを利用して高速化を図っています：TurboDiffusionは、低ビットのSageAttentionと訓練可能なSparse-Linear Attention (SLA)を使用して、注意の計算を高速化します。

(2)ステップ蒸留TurboDiffusionは効率的なステップ蒸留のためにrCMを採用しています。

(3) W8A8量子化：TurboDiffusionは、線形レイヤーを高速化し、モデルを圧縮するために、モデルパラメータと活性化を8ビットに量子化します。

加えて、TurboDiffusionには他にもいくつかの工学的最適化が組み込まれている。   

Wan2.2-I2V-14B-720P、Wan2.1-T2V-1.3B-480P、Wan2.1-T2V-14B-720P、Wan2.1-T2V-14B-480Pの各モデルで実験を行った。

実験結果によると、TurboDiffusionは、RTX 5090 GPU 1台でも、同等のビデオ品質を維持しながら、ビデオ生成で100～200倍のスピードアップを達成している。

モデルのチェックポイントや使いやすいコードを含むGitHubリポジトリは、https://github.com/thu-ml/TurboDiffusion。

Pages like I Fucking Love Science (IFLS), which has millions of followers and built its entire model around curating and sharing external science articles (often with a teaser image or caption), would be severely impacted if included in this restriction. The same goes for countless smaller or niche pages—science aggregators, news curators, meme pages linking to sources, or any content-sharing communities—that rely on posting multiple external links per day or week to drive traffic and engagement.  In the current limited test (started around December 16, 2025):  It primarily affects Facebook Pages and profiles in Professional Mode (used by creators, businesses, and public figures). Non-subscribed accounts are capped at a low number of organic posts containing external links per month (notifications often mention 2, though Meta says the exact limit varies by account in the test). To post unlimited (or significantly more) external links, the page/profile needs Meta Verified (starting at ~$14.99/month, higher tiers for businesses). Exemptions: Links in comments, affiliate links, and links to Meta-owned platforms (e.g., Instagram, WhatsApp, other Facebook content) are not restricted. Importantly, publishers (e.g., official news outlets) are explicitly not included in this test for now.  If this becomes permanent and expands:  Science pages like IFLS (which functions more as a curator/aggregator than a traditional publisher) could face a tough choice: Pay for Meta Verified (potentially scaling up costs for large pages), drastically reduce posting frequency, shift to native content (e.g., uploading articles as images/videos/Reels to keep users on-platform), or migrate audience-building efforts elsewhere (like TikTok, YouTube, or newsletters). Smaller pages might find the subscription unaffordable, effectively killing their organic reach strategy and forcing them to rely on paid ads or cross-posting internally.  Critics (including social media experts like Matt Navarra) argue this turns a once-free core feature—driving traffic off-platform—into a paid perk, pushing Meta's ecosystem to prioritize keeping users inside Facebook/Instagram. Meta frames it as adding value to subscribers, but it could fundamentally disrupt the open-web sharing model that built many of these pages.  For now, it's just a test with no announced rollout plans, but it's already sparking backlash from creators and brands dependent on external traffic. If your favorite pages start posting less or nudging toward subscriptions, this is likely why.
